Dear Chen: Thank you for reaching out to us about the Master of Science in Analytics program at Northwestern University

-----Original Message----- From: .
Dear Fan: Thank you for reaching out to us about the Master of Science in Analytics program at Northwestern University
To answer your questions: 1
We do not have any strict prerequisite courses, but we look for you to have taken calculus and statistics courses
We are more focused on the quantitative background when we are evaluating transcripts
In terms of computer science backgrounds, we provide a 2 week boot camp training session before our academic calendar begins
This boot camp brings in industry trainers from SQL, Cognos, SPSS, SAS, and Tableau to train our students
Some accepted students will enter the program with a background in Java and Python but it is not a requirement for applying
I encourage you to supply your UNM transcript
You can list it as a separate education experience in the online application
When you do so, it will allow me to upload your transcript under the correct heading, as opposed to uploading it as other 3
Your decision to take online courses in Coursera should be included in your resume or CV
Many accepted students went that route to strengthen their application
Any certification of your knowledge will help make you stand out against other applicants

Both GRE and GMAT test scores are accepted by the program, but neither are required for admission (though sending scores from one of the two tests is strongly encouraged to strengthen the application)

The admission for this program is very competitive and we do receive a lot of talented applicants, so industry experience, strong test scores, recommendations (a minimum of 3), and GPA are all taken into consideration
There is no formal GMAT or GRE cutoff score, but we do require a GPA of 3.0 or higher for consideration and enrollment is limited to 32 talented students each year
From: Fan Xiao .
Hello Bella: We accept 32 students a year
While this will undoubtedly mean that admission will be highly selective, it will also mean we can give appropriate attention to those who are admitted
We are aiming to foster a collaborative atmosphere within the program and believe that a small cohort of exceptionally talented and strongly motivated students will best enable us to achieve this
While we have many students enrolled in our program form CS and EE backgrounds we do not limit our admissions process to those academic majors
We look to build a collaborative cohort each year with a variety of backgrounds and interests
We have not had students in our program with a similar background to yours and I would be sure to mention that in your personal statement
As an academic institution we are very interested in applying analytics in a wide variety of fields of interest
I would not look at your background as weaker or negative, but unique

Background by Industry Experience (though industry experience is not required for consideration): 34% None, 28% Consulting and Professional Services, 22% Information Technology, 6% Academia, 6% Finance, 4% Engineering Please let me know what other questions and concerns you have about applying to our program

Hello Pradeep; I apologize for the delay in response time from our department

We are glad that there is an interest in our program, analytics is a growing field and our goal is to identify and assess the opportunities, needs and constraints for data usage within an organizational context; integrate information technology and data science to maximize the value of data; design innovative and creative data analytics solutions; communicate clearly and persuasively to a variety of audiences; lead analytics teams and projects
To answer your question concerning years of study and prerequisites, we look for graduation from an accredited university with a bachelors degree
Traditionally, we have accepted students from 4-year undergraduate programs, but that is not a requirement for our course
We require a minimum of a 3.0 GPA, 3 letters of recommendation, and a TOEFL/IELTS test
The GRE is recommended for students who feel that their quantitative abilities are not conveyed in their application, and when it strengthens a candidate
We do not require applicants to have background knowledge with all of the industry tools we use, such as Cognos, SAS, SPSS, SQL Tableau etc
We offer a two week boot camp before the fall quarter
We have industry representatives come to campus and train our students with these tools so they are prepared for their course work
We look for candidates with strong quantitative backgrounds, specifically stats, calculus, and algebra
Again I apologize for the delay in responding to you, please let me know what further questions you have and I will answer them to the best of my abilities

Hello Abhitab; I would be happy to answer your questions
In terms of flexibility of the program, we have so room for students to build what they want
If you have redundancies with courses we offer (say Java) then we will allow you to substitute with an approved course
Some quarters are more flexible than others, but if you are coming for the analytics education we have built all of the necessary courses and skill classes you will need into the curriculum
What were your concerns with the curriculum
Some of our students who are looking to tailor the program to their own research interests, will take on extra projects with Diego Klabjan
He has a great deal of industry projects happening at one time, currently 18 of our students have taken on additional projects to help pursue their fields of interest
Our classrooms are far from competitive
Our program is structured to be collaborative
Our main goal is to incorporate business skills in our classroom environment
We give our students ample opportunities to work on group projects and practicum project
Since the business world is built with analytical teams, we expect our students to be able to work in that environment
In terms of networking, we offer a weekly social on Thursdays
We invite companies to come on to campus and recruit from our students
Our students then participate in a relaxed and informal networking session
We also offer lunches to network with industry contacts who come onto campus

In the first 3 quarters our students are spending about 20+ hours a week attending classes, 5-10hours on their practicum project, and the remaining time is for them to complete project work and any additional tasks they have taken on
We typically build in days for working into their schedule when they will not have any classes
But their last quarter (the following Fall) our students are in class for 20 hours and working on their capstone project for about 20hours

Students do have downtime, some try to get involved with campus activities and they will go to football games together, but it is entirely up to the students what they do as a group in their free time
As the above answer indicates it is difficult for the students to have lots of free time to take part in extra activities but they do most things in a big group
Evanston is a mixture of college students, families, and young working professionals
There are many students in our program who have brought their families with them and they are able to find everything they need within Evanston
There is plenty of housing to accommodate and it is a suburb of Chicago, and very family friendly
Please let me know if you are looking for more detail to any of these questions
I am happy to help
